# MikroTik + Cursor: practical recommendations (RouterOS 6.49.13)

This note complements `mikrotik-cursor-refresh-ros64913.rsc`.

## Purpose

The script maintains a dynamic IPv4 address-list for Cursor-related domains.
It helps when your bypass logic is based on destination IP lists.

## Recommended baseline

- Script name: `cursor-refresh`
- Address-list: `cursor_bypass_v4`
- Scheduler interval: `1m` (or `30s` if reconnects are frequent)
- Entry timeout: `30m` (use `20m..60m` depending on network stability)

## Why frequent refresh is needed

`api2.cursor.sh` and CDN-backed domains can rotate through many IPs.
If refresh is too rare, router can keep stale/bad routes and Cursor may show
`reconnecting...`.

## Operational recommendations

1. Keep DNS working on router:
   - configure reachable DNS servers
   - ensure UDP/TCP 53 is not blocked for the router itself

2. Keep script schedule regular:
   - recommended: every 1 minute
   - for unstable links: every 30 seconds

3. Keep timeout moderate:
   - too long timeout keeps stale IPs
   - too short timeout can cause churn

4. Use comments for audit:
   - script tags entries as `cursor-auto <dns-name>`
   - this makes troubleshooting easier

5. Validate list growth:
   - monitor address-list size over time
   - if list grows too large, shorten timeout and keep 1m refresh

## Limitations of IP-based bypass

- Cloud IPs are shared and can host unrelated services.
- Domain-to-IP mapping can change quickly.
- Address-list bypass is less precise than domain/SNI-based policy.

If your gateway supports FQDN/SNI policies, prefer those for Cursor domains.

## Minimal domain scope for Cursor

- `*.cursor.sh`
- `*.cursorapi.com`
- `*.cursor-cdn.com`

Commonly observed related auth names:
- `*.workosdns.com`
- `*.workos-dns.com`

## Useful checks on MikroTik

Print managed entries:

```rsc
/ip firewall address-list print where list="cursor_bypass_v4"
```

Force one update run:

```rsc
/system script run cursor-refresh
```

Check scheduler:

```rsc
/system scheduler print where name="cursor-refresh"
```

View script logs:

```rsc
/log print where message~"cursor-refresh"
```
